<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-27T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-27T20:00:00-05:00" n="628" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d628">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3356: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moore</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-27T20:00:00-05:00">April 27, 1929—8
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 10 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>86. I assume that my telegram number 84<note n="29" xml:id="d628fn29"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_780">p.
                                780</ref>.</note> which probably reached you after you had sent your
                                49<note n="29" xml:id="d628fn31"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_780">p. 780</ref>.</note> to me answers this
                            telegram and also your 48.<note n="30" xml:id="d628fn30"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_779">p.
                                779</ref>.</note> Am I correct?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>